00:07:19.310 --> 00:07:23.770
&gt;&gt; MILDRED LOVING: I'd say I
think that marrying who you want

00:07:23.770 --> 00:07:27.870
to is a right that no man
should have anything to do with.

00:07:27.870 --> 00:07:30.620
It's a God-given right, I think.

00:07:30.620 --> 00:07:32.590
&gt;&gt; HOPE RYDEN: Mildred loving
married the boy next door,

00:07:32.590 --> 00:07:33.890
Richard Loving.

00:07:33.890 --> 00:07:35.500
Richard Loving is a
construction worker,

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:37.800
Mildred Loving the
daughter of a share cropper.

00:07:37.800 --> 00:07:39.480
They were born and
raised in Caroline County,

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:42.100
Virginia where white and
colored people seem unaware

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:45.360
of the racial prejudice that
exists in much of the country.

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:47.910
The Lovings didn't know that it
was a crime for a white person

00:07:47.910 --> 00:07:49.630
to marry a negro in Virginia.

00:07:49.630 --> 00:07:50.930
They found out the hard way.

00:07:50.930 --> 00:07:57.370 position:56%
&gt;&gt; MILDRED LOVING: I didn't realize
how bad it was until we got married.

00:07:57.370 --> 00:07:58.670
&gt;&gt; HOPE RYDEN: Full
of love themselves,

00:07:58.670 --> 00:08:00.870
they didn't expect to
find hate in others.

00:08:00.870 --> 00:08:03.470
Their home swarms with
children, their own three,

00:08:03.470 --> 00:08:07.270
as well as neighborhood friends
who enjoy the warmth here.

00:08:07.270 --> 00:08:11.610
Mrs. Loving recalls how the
ordeal began one night in 1958.

00:08:11.610 --> 00:08:14.400
&gt;&gt; MILDRED LOVING: The
night we were arrested.

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:23.740 position:56%
I guess it was about 2:00 a.m. and
I saw this light you know and I woke

00:08:23.740 --> 00:08:27.440
up and it was the policeman
standing beside the bed.

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:33.420
He told us to get up,
and we was under arrest.

00:08:33.420 --> 00:08:35.200
&gt;&gt; RICHARD LOVING:
You go ahead and play.

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:37.900
&gt;&gt; MILDRED LOVING: Then,
anyway, they carried us

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:41.060
to Bowling Green and
they locked us up.

00:08:41.060 --> 00:08:45.440
In January, they had the
trial, and they told us

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:49.210
to leave the state for 25 years.

00:08:49.210 --> 00:08:51.810
But the way I understood it, the
lawyer said that we could come back

00:08:51.810 --> 00:08:54.930
to visit when we wanted to.

00:08:54.930 --> 00:09:00.440
So, that Easter, we came
back and they got us again.

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:01.950
&gt;&gt; RICHARD LOVING: We had been
there a few times before that,

00:09:01.950 --> 00:09:04.080
but at Easter we came down,
they found out we was down,

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:05.990
and they arrested us again.

00:09:05.990 --> 00:09:08.170
&gt;&gt; HOPE RYDEN: The Lovings spent
five years in a negro ghetto

00:09:08.170 --> 00:09:11.140
in Washington, DC where they
suffered the indignities

00:09:11.140 --> 00:09:14.140
of unemployment, loneliness,
and uncertainty.

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:17.860
When one of the children, unused
to city streets, was hit by a car,

00:09:17.860 --> 00:09:19.980
Mrs. Loving decided to act.

00:09:19.980 --> 00:09:21.850
She wrote a letter to
the then Attorney General

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:23.970
of the United States,
Robert Kennedy,

00:09:23.970 --> 00:09:27.820
who in turn passed the letter on to
a Virginia lawyer, Bernard Cohen,

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:31.280
a member of the Civil
Liberties Union.

00:09:31.280 --> 00:09:32.580
&gt;&gt; BERNARD COHEN: "We
have three children

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:33.880
and cannot afford an attorney.

00:09:33.880 --> 00:09:36.490
We wrote to the Attorney General
and he suggested that we get

00:09:36.490 --> 00:09:38.490
in touch with you for advice.

00:09:38.490 --> 00:09:39.790
Please help us if you can.

00:09:39.790 --> 00:09:41.450
Hope to hear from you real soon.

00:09:41.450 --> 00:09:44.390
Yours truly, Mr. and
Mrs. Richard Loving."

00:09:44.390 --> 00:09:49.160
It was that simple letter that got
us into this not-so-simple case.

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:51.750
&gt;&gt; HOPE RYDEN: Bernard Cohen
could and did help the Lovings.

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:55.710
He teamed up with another attorney,
Phil Hirschkop, and at no fee,

00:09:55.710 --> 00:09:58.560
they reopened the Loving
case in the Virginia courts,

00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:00.540
appealing each losing decision

00:10:00.540 --> 00:10:03.580 position:56%
until at last the United States
Supreme Court heard these arguments.

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:06.230
&gt;&gt; PHILL HIRSCHKOP:
Arguing for protection,

00:10:06.230 --> 00:10:10.390 position:56%
we advanced the arguments that
these statutes are slavery statutes.

00:10:10.390 --> 00:10:12.320
They're meant to keep
the negro people

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:14.660
in the badges and bonds of slavery.

00:10:14.660 --> 00:10:16.200
&gt;&gt; BERNARD COHEN: The
outrageous civil effects

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:20.700
of these statutes are not
always apparent right away.

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:23.960
For example, if Richard
Loving were to die,

00:10:23.960 --> 00:10:25.880
then Mildred Loving
would not be able

00:10:25.880 --> 00:10:28.220
to collect social security
benefits as his widow.

00:10:28.220 --> 00:10:30.250
&gt;&gt; PHILL HIRSCHKOP: What is
fundamentally important, though,

00:10:30.250 --> 00:10:35.210
is we asked the court to decide
that a state may not pass a law

00:10:35.210 --> 00:10:38.430
which proscribes marriage
between two consenting,

00:10:38.430 --> 00:10:41.660
competent adults based
on race alone.

00:10:41.660 --> 00:10:42.980
&gt;&gt; HOPE RYDEN: The
attorneys for the state

00:10:42.980 --> 00:10:45.460
of Virginia refused
to talk with ABC.

00:10:45.460 --> 00:10:47.680
Bernard Cohen describes
their arguments.

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:48.980 position:56%
&gt;&gt; BERNARD COHEN: They seemed to say

00:10:48.980 --> 00:10:51.720
that there was a present day
justification for these laws.

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:55.630
That is that they're
interested in the welfare

00:10:55.630 --> 00:10:57.790
of the children of such marriages.

00:10:57.790 --> 00:11:00.060
&gt;&gt; HOPE RYDEN: Today, the United
States Supreme Court handed

00:11:00.060 --> 00:11:01.470
down a decision.

00:11:01.470 --> 00:11:04.270 position:56%
The Lovings' ordeal is at last over.

00:11:04.270 --> 00:11:07.680
Richard and Mildred Loving have
won the right to be man and wife,

00:11:07.680 --> 00:11:10.490
father and mother, in
the state of Virginia.

00:11:10.490 --> 00:11:13.740
Anti-miscegenation laws have
been declared illegal not only

00:11:13.740 --> 00:11:18.130
in Virginia but in all 16 states
that have held such statutes.

00:11:18.130 --> 00:11:25.420
This is Hope Ryden,
ABC News, reporting.

