00:15:11.240 --> 00:15:14.610
So, let's begin the legal
discussion by going back

00:15:14.610 --> 00:15:17.180
to the post-Civil War period.

00:15:17.180 --> 00:15:19.740
There were three important
amendments that were adopted

00:15:19.740 --> 00:15:22.820
at that time, and the goal was

00:15:22.820 --> 00:15:28.120
to fundamentally change the
status of the former slaves.

00:15:28.120 --> 00:15:31.470
So, the 13th amendment
abolished slavery.

00:15:31.470 --> 00:15:34.470
We'll go back to the 14th
amendment in a minute.

00:15:34.470 --> 00:15:40.930 position:56%
The 15th amendment gave the right to
vote, denied the ability of a state

00:15:40.930 --> 00:15:44.610
to withhold the vote from
people on the basis of race.

00:15:44.610 --> 00:15:46.080
Of course, you have to realize

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:49.390
that that only affected
African American men.

00:15:49.390 --> 00:15:52.280
African American women had
to wait another 50 years,

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:55.780
along with all women in this
country, to get the right to vote.

00:15:55.780 --> 00:16:00.880 position:56%
The 14th amendment, which is the one
that was most involved in this case,

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:05.560
is the amendment that guaranteed
two things, that an individual

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:08.650
in a state could not be
deprived of life, liberty,

00:16:08.650 --> 00:16:13.230
or property without what's
called due process of law,

00:16:13.230 --> 00:16:16.830
and the second was to
guarantee the equal protection

00:16:16.830 --> 00:16:20.340
of the laws in the states.

00:16:20.340 --> 00:16:26.100 position:56%
So, what did equal protection of
the laws mean for the former slaves?

00:16:26.100 --> 00:16:29.460
The Supreme Court answered
that in 1896

00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:33.080
in a case titled Plessy
vs. Ferguson.

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:36.870
Plessy vs. Ferguson came out
of the state of Louisiana.

00:16:36.870 --> 00:16:40.230
Louisiana had a law that said that
black people and white people have

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:42.650
to be separated in railroad cars.

00:16:42.650 --> 00:16:46.980
They cannot sit together in the
same car, let alone the same seat.

00:16:46.980 --> 00:16:51.600
Homer Plessy challenged that law,
and he, as you might imagine,

00:16:51.600 --> 00:16:55.020 position:56%
assumed that with the passage of
the 14th amendment and the guarantee

00:16:55.020 --> 00:16:59.940
of equal treatment under the law
that that law would be struck down.

00:16:59.940 --> 00:17:01.890
That didn't happen.

00:17:01.890 --> 00:17:06.480
The Supreme Court determined that
the states could separate people

00:17:06.480 --> 00:17:10.140
by race as long as
things were equal.

00:17:10.140 --> 00:17:18.100
This doctrine of "separate but
equal" was a doctrine that lasted

00:17:18.100 --> 00:17:24.430
for a long time and allowed states
to pass laws, which they did,

00:17:24.430 --> 00:17:28.920
that either required or allowed
the separation of people by race

00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:37.390
in movie theaters, in restaurants,
in libraries, in restrooms.

00:17:37.390 --> 00:17:39.320
During that period of time also was

00:17:39.320 --> 00:17:43.590
when Virginia passed the Racial
Integrity Act, which is described.

00:17:43.590 --> 00:17:47.960
If you look at the slide,
it's in the bottom middle.

00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:50.970
The Virginia Bulletin
explains this act.

00:17:50.970 --> 00:17:56.410
It basically said that white and
non-white people cannot marry,

00:17:56.410 --> 00:18:00.870
and if they do, it's a crime.

00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:05.250
So, this was what we had as
law, "separate but equal,"

00:18:05.250 --> 00:18:08.170
laws like the State of
Virginia's that prohibited marriage

00:18:08.170 --> 00:18:13.450
between people of different
races until 1954.

00:18:13.450 --> 00:18:19.030
And in 1954, the Supreme Court
decided the case of Brown vs. Board

00:18:19.030 --> 00:18:22.840
of Education, and I'm sure
you've all heard about that.

00:18:22.840 --> 00:18:26.800
That was the case where the court
looked at this whole "separate

00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:31.850
but equal" doctrine and determined,
and if you look at the same slide,

00:18:31.850 --> 00:18:35.740
to the left, bottom left,
Brown vs. Board of Education,

00:18:35.740 --> 00:18:39.380
there's the important language
where the Court said when it comes

00:18:39.380 --> 00:18:45.090
to education, separate
is inherently unequal,

00:18:45.090 --> 00:18:48.110
meaning there's no
way there's equality

00:18:48.110 --> 00:18:52.100
when the state says black
children have to go to school here,

00:18:52.100 --> 00:18:55.600
white children have
to go to school there.

00:18:55.600 --> 00:18:58.000
Totally unacceptable.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:01.560
That ushered in what
we call the period

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:05.560
of a new Civil Rights
Movement, if you will.

00:19:05.560 --> 00:19:10.550
And two important events
happened the next year, in 1955.

00:19:10.550 --> 00:19:16.510
In August of 1955,
14-year-old Emmett Till was

00:19:16.510 --> 00:19:19.320
in Mississippi and he was murdered.

00:19:19.320 --> 00:19:21.240
He was murdered why?

00:19:21.240 --> 00:19:25.480
Because it's alleged that
he insulted a white woman.

00:19:25.480 --> 00:19:26.780
How did he insult her?

00:19:26.780 --> 00:19:30.240
He either whistled or he
said something to her.

00:19:30.240 --> 00:19:31.540
That's it.

00:19:31.540 --> 00:19:38.370
And then in December of 1955, I
know you remember, Rosa Parks,

00:19:38.370 --> 00:19:42.540
Mrs. Rosa Parks, refused to give
up her seat on a bus in Montgomery,

00:19:42.540 --> 00:19:47.250
Alabama, and the Montgomery
bus boycott started.

00:19:47.250 --> 00:19:53.020
After that, in 1955, one
other important thing,

00:19:53.020 --> 00:19:56.380
the state of Virginia
announced that it would engage

00:19:56.380 --> 00:20:00.160
in massive resistance to
the Supreme Court decision

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:02.060
